Part I - DATA ANALYSIS ON THE PISA DATASET¶

by Igweze Ifeanyi¶

Introduction¶

This is a dataset which examines how well students have learned the school curricullum and how well prepared they are for life beyond school, all from 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

In [10]:
df['Parents Presence'] = ((df['Mother Present'] == 'No') | (df['Father Present'] == 'No')).replace(False, 'Both').replace(True, 'Single')

#dropping the former columns
df = df.drop(['Mother Present','Father Present'], axis=1)

Type issues:

  • Study Time With Parent is a float64 instead of an int64
  • Gender, ParentsHighestEducation and ImmigrationStatus are meant to be categories

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

A dataset of 11 features and 258484 student results.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I would like to know what parental factors affect student scores the most.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Based on the fact parents are given in this dataset, I think:

  1. the time the parent spends working with the student
  2. the level of education of the parents
  3. the presence of the parents at home

Univariate Exploration¶

1. How much time does the parent spend working with the student?¶

In [16]:
fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(17, 8), sharex=True)

sb.boxplot(y=df['Study Time With Parent'], ax=ax1[0]);
ax1[0].set(ylabel='No. of hours')

five = df[df['Study Time With Parent'] < 6]['Study Time With Parent'].value_counts()

patches, texts, autotexts = ax1[1].pie(five, 
                                    colors = ['#008080','#008B8B','#5F9EA0','#20B2AA','#00CED1','#48D1CC'],
                                    labels=['No time spent with parent(s)', '1 hour', '2 hours', '3 hours', '4 hours', '5 hours'], 
                                    autopct='%1.1f%%',
                                    startangle=180
                                   );   
for text in autotexts:
    text.set_color('white')
ax1[1].axis('equal');

plt.suptitle('Study time with parent(s) distribution')
plt.show();

Inference:

  1. Though a good amount of students work with their parents at their own rates, a vast majority of students do not work withtheir parents.

  2. Some students work as much as 30 hours with their parents.

2. Level of education of the parents¶

In [17]:
plt.figure(figsize=[16, 12]);
sb.countplot(x = 'Parents Highest Education', data = df, color = sb.color_palette()[0]);

n_points = df.shape[0]
cat_counts = df['Parents Highest Education'].value_counts()
locs, labels = plt.xticks()

for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

    count = cat_counts[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_points)

    plt.text(loc, count-8, pct_string, ha = 'center', va='bottom', color = 'black')

plt.ylabel('No. of parents');
plt.xlabel('');
plt.title('Parents Level of Education', y = 1.02);

Inference

  1. Most parents reach the upper secondary education level
  2. No parent got the second stage of the tertiary education

Bivariate Exploration¶

1. Parent Presence vs Score¶

In [35]:
data = pd.melt(df, id_vars=['Student Id', 'Gender', 'Country', 'Study Time With Parent', 'Parents Highest Education', 'Immigration Status', 'Parents Presence'], 
               value_vars=['Average Score','Math Score','Reading Score','Science Score'], 
               var_name="Score Type", value_name='Score')
data['Score Type'] = data['Score Type'].replace('Average Score', 'Average').replace('Math Score','Math').replace('Reading Score','Reading').replace('Science Score','Science')

palette = ["#40E0D0", "#008080"]

plt.figure(figsize = [15, 14])
ax = sb.violinplot(x = 'Score', y='Score Type', hue='Parents Presence',
                   data=data, palette=palette, split=True,
                   scale="count", inner="quartile");

x_ticks = np.arange(0, 1000 + 1, 100)
plt.xticks(x_ticks, x_ticks);
plt.title("Score distribution based on parent presence");

Inference:

  1. Compared to those of students living with two parents, the scores of students living with a single parent is significanlty less (by about 20 points).

2. Parents level of education vs Scores¶

In [37]:
parents_he_scores = df[['Parents Highest Education','Average Score','Math Score','Reading Score','Science Score']]
parents_he_scores.rename({'Average Score':'Average', 'Math Score':'Math', 'Reading Score':'Reading', 'Science Score':'Science'},axis=1, inplace=True)
data = pd.melt(parents_he_scores, id_vars=['Parents Highest Education'], 
               value_vars=['Average','Math','Reading','Science'], 
               var_name="Score Type", value_name='Score Value')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(14, 12))

ax = sb.pointplot(ax=ax, data = data, 
                  x = 'Parents Highest Education', y='Score Value', hue='Score Type', 
                  dodge=0.3, palette=sb.color_palette('husl', 8), 
                  markers=["o", "x","x","x"], linestyles=["-", "--", "--", "--"]);

ax.set(xlabel='Parent Highest Education', ylabel='Score')
plt.title("How parent(s) education impact the student socres ?", y=1.02);

Inference:

  1. Students with parents who reach upper secondary or beyond tend to perform above average
  2. The higher the parent education level, the higher the student score

3. Study time with parent(s) vs Scores¶

In [43]:
scores = df.groupby(['Study Time With Parent']).mean().reset_index()[['Study Time With Parent','Average Score','Math Score','Reading Score','Science Score']]
scores.rename({'Average Score':'Average', 'Math Score':'Math', 'Reading Score':'Reading', 'Science Score':'Science'}, axis=1, inplace=True)
data = pd.melt(scores, id_vars=['Study Time With Parent'], 
               value_vars=['Average','Math','Reading','Science'], 
               var_name="Score Type", value_name='Score')

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(25, 8))

sb.lineplot(ax=ax[0], data = data, 
            x = 'Study Time With Parent', y='Score', hue='Score Type'
           );
ax[0].set(title='Impact on the scores mean', xlabel='No. of hours', ylabel='Score')

sb.heatmap(df[['Average Score','Math Score','Reading Score', 'Science Score', 'Study Time With Parent']].corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
           cmap = 'Reds', center = 0)
ax[1].set(title='Correlation between the time students spend studying with their parent(s) and scores')

plt.suptitle("Student performace based on whether they study with their parent", y=1.02);

Inference:

  1. when considering only number of hours between 0 and 5, there's a significant drop of about 70 points in the score so studying with parents does not seems to be a factor of success.

  2. From the visualization correlations, we get the confirmation that there's a weak negative correlation between scores and study time with parent. This looks normal since we expect of students from that age to be autonomous.

4. Immigration status vs Scores¶

In [44]:
data = pd.melt(df, id_vars=['Student Id', 'Gender', 'Country', 'Study Time With Parent', 'Parents Highest Education', 'Immigration Status', 'Parents Presence'], 
               value_vars=['Average Score','Math Score','Reading Score','Science Score'], 
               var_name="Score Type", value_name='Score')
data['Score Type'] = data['Score Type'].replace('Average Score', 'Average').replace('Math Score','Math').replace('Reading Score','Reading').replace('Science Score','Science')

plt.figure(figsize=[12, 16]);
sb.boxplot(x = data['Score Type'], y = data['Score'], hue=data['Immigration Status'], palette = sb.color_palette('husl', 8))
plt.title('Relationship between immigration status and scores');
y_ticks = np.arange(0, 1000 + 1, 100)
plt.yticks(y_ticks, y_ticks);

Inference:

  1. From an overall point of view, studying seems slighly easier for native students, but the difference in score remains quite little.
  2. In Math, scores are similar between native and second generation students while the one for first generation is a bit less.
